# UI reuse and design tokens

Visual work must stay consistent with **what already exists in the codebase** and with **`docs/FRONTEND.md`** (colors, typography, components). Do not invent parallel systems.

## Before adding anything new

1. **Search** for existing components, layout primitives, and shared styles (e.g. `components/`, `ui/`, theme files, CSS variables, Tailwind config).
2. **Prefer composition**: extend or wrap an existing component instead of duplicating markup and styles.
3. **Tokens first**: use named tokens, theme values, or documented palette/typography from `docs/FRONTEND.md`—not arbitrary hex/RGB or ad-hoc font stacks.

## When something seems missing

- **Necessary** means: no reasonable existing primitive or token can express the requirement without breaking the design system.
- Prefer the **smallest** change: add one token or one variant to an existing component, not a new standalone pattern.
- If the product doc does not cover a new visual need, **propose updating `docs/FRONTEND.md`** (or the project’s token source) instead of silently diverging.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — one-off styling, ignores shared Button and palette
<button style={{ background: "#ff00aa", fontFamily: "Comic Sans MS" }}>Save</button>

// ✅ GOOD — existing component + tokens / theme
<Button variant="primary">Save</Button>
```

```css
/* ❌ BAD — magic values alongside an existing token system */
.card { color: #333333; border: 1px solid #cccccc; }

/* ✅ GOOD — semantic token / variable already used in the project */
.card { color: var(--color-text-primary); border: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
```
